==English==

===Etymology===
from Cuckoo, a bird that lays its eggs in another's nest.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|cuckold|cuckolds}}
# A [[man]] [[married]] to an [[unfaithful]] [[wife]] (latterly one who condones or tolerates her unfaithfulness).

===Verb===
{{en-verb|cuckold|cuckolds|cuckolded|cuckolding}}
#{{transitive}} To make a cuckold of someone by being unfaithful.

===Examples===
William Shakespeare:

    Now, sir, who's a cuckold now?
    --Merry Wives of Windsor: V, v
 
    I will chop her into messes: cuckold me!
    --Othello: IV, i

    Use her as the key of the cuckoldly rogue's coffer
    --Merry Wives of Windsor: II, ii 


